Development of the rice prices since 1989 
Until 1989, the SSR only five authorized state agencies: edok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist. 
The travel agents at the time, above all, sold only travel in the socialist Eastern Bloc countries, in the West at that time were chosen. 
And so, Czech tourists travelled to the Baltic Sea (in the German Democratic Republic (GDR), in the Soviet Union (Sochi on the Crimea peninsula on the Black Sea), to the Black Sea to Bulgaria and Romania and Hungary to the Balaton. 
One exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when it also was allowed to travel to Yugoslavia, Yugoslavia then proposed a pro-Western course, and that is why the trips to Yugoslavia have been severely restricted. 
A great paradox of the socialist era was that it was not even citizens of the Soviet bloc (Tschechoslowakes) was allowed in the framework of the socialist countries to travel freely. 
If a citizen of the SSR individually for Poland, for example, or even in the Soviet Union wanted to travel, then he needed a so-called invitation letter, because otherwise, individual travel was not possible. 
Even then, the travel agencies offered trips to the West, but huge queues had to accept or even in sleeping bags to be careful before the travel office, or at least "good friend" in the travel office. 
Even so, the issue has not gone for a long time. 
The so-called foreign exchange commitment - the condition for an exit in the West - was only "politically reliable" people - the others were not allowed to travel at all. 
The Czechoslovak currency was not a free umtauschbare currency without foreign exchange commitment, so it would have been impossible to make the necessary financial resources (Western currency) for a trip to the West. 
The majority of Czechs spent their holidays at home, no wonder that the Czechs bought countless weekend houses and dachas - a habit that lasted until now. 
The Velvet Revolution of 1989 was followed by a travel revolution of the Czechs on the foot. 
While until 1989, a holiday in the GDR or in Bulgaria was the measure of all things, the Czechs spent 4.5 million last year on their foreign holidays in countries of the world. 
An enormous paradox today is no longer conscious at all is the fact that the currently most popular tourist destination of the Czechs - Croatia until 1989 could not travel at all, because it is part of the former Yugoslavia. 
Right from the beginning of the 1990s of the last century to the foreign exchange requirement was lifted into the neighbouring Western European countries, which is a huge wave of short visit to Vienna in Austria and Germany. 
The Tschechoslowakes have for a long time from their trips to the West simply cannot get enough, everyone wanted at least a few days ago. 
For example, the Czech tourists slept on trips to Paris in a tent in the park, because who would have the money for a shelter in the hotel or in a pension. 
A typical feature on foreign travel of Czechs was a canned beer and sausage, etc., loaded baggage. 
Another important milestone was the introduction of the free umtauschbaren Czech crown - after decades our tourists were finally free to buy the Western currency. 
Our living standards and the average salary rose to 1997, einmündete in another important moment. 
Thanks to the increased demand for travel, travel agents began regularly in 1997, preparing to travel by charter flights, which makes the air travel, thanks to the ability to negotiate quantity rabatte, compared to the past verbilligten unbelievable. 
At the end of the 1990s the Czechs, except the United States, foreign currency transactions with all the advanced countries in the world, which travel more easily. 
Another interesting moment in the history of the "velvet" tourist traffic in the year 2000, when, thanks to the high demand for the first direct charter flight was processed in an exotic country after Thailand. 
Since then, every year to fly direct charter planes with Czech passengers in far-off sunny countries; this year it flies directly from the Czech Republic to 12 exotic destinations. 
The Tsd 100 Czechs travel each year in exotic countries. 
Another important moment in the era that our "revolutionary" development marked came in 2008. 
On 17 November 2008, the US visa requirement for Czech tourists, making our country brutalized for daring definitely among the advanced countries in the world. 
In 2008, the Czechs spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50,3%) and for the first time in its history for a single holiday trip, including the cost of the holiday more than CZK 15 Tsd per capita. 
The main aim is to find a new chairman - once again threatens a stalemate. 
For nearly five months, the Czech football no chairman and threatens the Ivan Hašek successor at the head of the Czech Football Association (FAR), not even after the extraordinary general meeting on Thursday will be known in Nymburk. 
To date, there is still no agreement on how the electoral system is to be elected. 
And without them there is no vote on the three potential successors. 
Three interested parties want to manage the Czech football - Jindich Rajchl, Miroslav Pelta and Tomáš Paclík. 
In June, Hašek resigned from his post, and his colleagues urged the departure had to reach an agreement and to find a strong personality, which could lead the football in future. 
However, in the era after Hašek broke the old quarrels between the two chambers were once again not be able to agree on a joint candidate. 
This was quite clear on 16 September, when the new chairman should be chosen. 
The main assembly delegates were in vain in the House of Commons in Prague's Smíchov district, because the trial produced no result, and it was not just about the election itself. 
You could not even agree who actually entitled to the full collection - only the statutory representatives or officials equipped with a full power. 
In this single point reached at least partial agreement, including the recommendation of the Institute for State and Law, whose opinion a representation at full power base was not admissible. 
The disputes over the electoral system, however, continue to persist. 
The executive committee did not bring more clarity on the matter at its meetings - no matter whether ordinary or extraordinary, in principle, absolutely nothing else on the agenda. 
Even if the views expressed in relation to the election changed a few times - the central point remained the same. 
The question is: how should we proceed in the third round, in order to avoid a stalemate? 
"The bone of contention is the question whether we should proceed in accordance with the Statute, or whether an entirely different model needs to be found," said Duan Svoboda, one of the three nden leaders of the FAR, who represents in the management of professional football. 
According to satzungsmäßigem model triumphs in the third round of the one candidate who receives the greater expressed as support in the chamber, for which he is standing. 
Moravia is reportedly ready to respond to the compromise, that the one candidate to win the higher number of votes from both chambers. 
The Czech side, in turn, is on the condition that the winner in the percentage of the vote count at least a two-thirds majority. 
"Then, the two Vorrundes have absolutely no sense, this modus operandi would question the whole concept of bicameral," Svoboda understands the objections of the Moravian side, it would be best not to bend the electoral system, but according to choose applicable statutes. 
Surprisingly, this is also true Tomáš Paclík, even if it emerges that the statutory order of all the candidates most likely Pelta. 
"My wish is that as much as possible will be elected in accordance with the Statute." 
"This is no nonsensical ersatz variants to be invented, as in the last general meeting," said the owner (of the football club), Victoria Plze, who is standing for the first time, and above all in its opinions from Pelta to abgrenzte. 
Pelta, however, remains optimistic. 
In his opinion, it will be known in Nymburk as the new chairman, and he believes that the candidates in the future will cooperate constructively. 
"The possible qualification of the national team for the Euro on this day would certainly help to calm the emotions." 
"If the football first ride on the euphoric wave, it is also the willingness to cooperate more," said the official from Jablonec, all three of the Adepten has the most experience, both on a professional, as well as regional levels. 
Rajchl is more circumspect. 
"I hope for an agreement, but unfortunately the situation is mixed." 
"This is not a matter between the people from their homes in Bohemia and Moravia, but there are certain rules for their own purposes," zurechtzubiegen ."" 
"That is why it is not ruled out a new blockage in the main assembly." 
"I hope, however, that common sense prevails in the end," Rajchl said. 
The only thing - much time remains for the agreement of all sides. 
Some negotiations should take place allegedly directly in Montenegro, but who knows whether the football generalität until qualification will be complete. 
The charter plane, which, among other Dalibor Kuera and Rajchl should fly to Podgorice in the morning in Prague did not start because of a technical disruption and so feverish for an alternative option, as a part of the executive committee but has yet to get to the site of the Barrage-Hinspiels. 
Ultimately, it is surely the meeting at ministerial level crucial to which it is supposed to come on Wednesday. 
Josef Dobe, the minister for education, youth and physical education, the divided parties would have liked to within the country's largest sports associations to reach an agreement. 
There is a lot at stake: state aid, the Vertrauungswürdigkeit of the Czech football and the upcoming general meeting of the STV, the Czech sport in the wake of the financial problems of Sazka the new direction. 
