Peter Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist. 
He is also the new permanent secretary of the Swedish Academy, which determines the Nobel Prize for literature. 
He has written an unusual book that he was not incorrect as "a work of history." 
It contains only a few big names and big contracts or famous battles, and there are hardly any ambassadors, reporters or discussions about tactics and equipment. 
It is not so much a book about what happened, he says, but rather "a book about how it was." it is of "feelings, ideas, experiences and sentiments." 
"Beauty and horror" almost the war experiences of 20 more or less concealed men and women on both sides of the war, from schoolgirls and Botanikern to mountaineers, doctors, drivers and office workers. 
Some of these people are heroes. 
Some prisoners of war, lose limb will be crazy or die. 
Each of these lives flackert such as the Votivkerzen in a church, some, while others lapse. 
Englunds book differs from the usual history books. 
It also corrected the notion that the First World War had just been the devastating war on the West Front. 
"Beauty and horror" with experts on other war zones: the Alps, the Balkans, the Ostfront, Mesopotamia, East Africa. 
