Some stories act of honor and bravery. 
An American acknowledges his own drive for ferocity and says about the war: "We feel that this is, after all, what was planned for men rather than to sit on the Lehnstuhl, with the evening newspaper or the bestselling book and a cigarette and a whisky in hand, and to do so, as a façade civilization and as if there were no barbarism behind its own strengthened and besch were brust hemd." 
Conversely, a British soldier acknowledges that he will probably die and no one notice or will look into this. 
"If the idea to sacrifice themselves, we would like to think that this is happening before an audience," he writes. 
Instead, it is so terrible as "a condemned man, who was hanged in secret." 
Other observations from the old Europe, which falls apart, and on new types of terror. 
