Six people said as a character in the name of the alleged perpetrator, who was ultimately acquitted. 
"I still remember the day when the verdict was read out," Lyman says. 
"I thought the labor would use. I ran screaming from the courtroom." 
"They brought me into the psychiatric department and I remember that when I came out again, I said to my commander: this was not his trial, and that was my trial." 
Lyman was invited to visit a military psychiater, in the end, a diagnostizierte personality disorder and declared them incompetent. 
In January 2010, she was sacked dishonourable, so that it receives no support. 
Whether or not the complaint, the Lyman and the other claimants have submitted is pure speculation, says John Turley, a professor of jurisprudence at the George Washington University Law School. 
Nevertheless, he notes: "I think they should move forward." 
As far as between them and a verdict is this doctrine, which has been criticized since, for the first time it has been called into question. 
I am a critic of the Feres-Doktrin. 
The military lags a decade later, because they do not have the same incentive and the same deterrence, which entails a liability. 
He adds: "The odds are against them... but it is important for them that they are trying to do." 
These things will only change if good people are ready to fight. 
