Japan will be reborn after the earthquake 
The GDP is growing by 1,5% thanks to domestic consumption and put an end to the spiral of free fall from the beginning of March 
Since the last March was paralyzed the Japanese economy, which is still in the recovery after the devastating earthquake, the einmündete into a nuclear crisis and the worst catastrophe that Japan had lived through the Second World War. 
The initial estimates of the government in Tokyo evaluated the damage to 300 000 dollars, a blow that despite the difficult global economic situation, it seems to weaken. 
After three quarters were permanent nden case, the data on gross domestic product from July to September, finally to close this chapter: the GDP grew by 1,5% compared to the previous quarter and by 6% to the average estimate for the year. 
The measured value in the second quarter - in Japan the year begins in March 2012 - is also the fastest growth since the period from January to March 2010. 
The recovery can partly through the sale of machinery for the rebuilding of the earthquake and subsequent tsunami devastated areas will be declared. 
In fact, the companies increased their investments by 1,1% compared with the decline of 0,9% for capital investments, which were recorded from January to March, the first decline in unaufhaltsamer increases after six months. 
Nevertheless, the real turnaround of the Japanese economy is not exclusively from Keynesian stimulus, using the crisis to build infrastructure or build new. 
Aufgewacht, Japan, in particular, thanks to the development of domestic consumption, which currently accounts for 60% of Japan's GDP. 
This variable rose by 1%, initiated by the growing spending on cars, travel and leisure activities. 
The stigma of the yen 
Tokyo has been entrusted to the domestic market after the yen - Japanese currency - in one of the "safe currencies" of investors, before the debt crisis in the euro zone and the gloomy forecasts for the SA to flee, a privilege as a gravestone rests on the accounts of export companies. 
With a stronger currency, the products are more expensive abroad, a serious problem for a country whose economy is based on the health of the major technology producers. 
Toyota and Sony, for example, had its weak trading results from July to September on the listing of the yen. 
While the markets continue to besieged the peripheral countries, the government Yoshihiko Noda remains vigilant. 
"We must pay attention to the continuing risks, for example, to the deterioration of some foreign economies, the impact of the floods in Thailand and the rapid appreciation of the yen," said yesterday the state secretary for economic policy, Motohisa Furukawa. 
The prospects are not really very aufheiternd. 
The Organisation for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD) said that the majority of Member States in September, clearer signs of a slowdown in economic development. 
The indicator of the turning points of the global economy has brought to light, that would be drawn from the greatest economic potential for the brakes. 
It fell by four tenths up to 100,4 points compared to the 100,8 in August. 
The euro zone is even below the average of 100, after it fell by eight points to 99.13 points. 
